==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wivern
<hw>Wiv"ern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wivere</ets> a serpent, OF.
<ets>wivre</ets>, <ets>guivre</ets>, F. <ets>givre</ets>,
<ets>guivre</ets>, wiver, from L. <ets>vipera</ets>; probably influenced
by OHG. <ets>wipera</ets>, from the Latin. See <er>Viper</er>, and cf.
<er>Weever</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A fabulous two-legged, winged
creature, like a cockatrice, but having the head of a dragon, and
without spurs.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>wyvern</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The jargon of heraldry, its griffins, its mold warps, its
<qex>wiverns</qex>, and its dragons.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The weever.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wives</ent>⟦br⟧
